Excellent work! Many thanks!
Excellent work! Many thanks!
This is worth moving to an earlier file. You could use `IntermediateField.inclusion` to help golf this.
Thank you for your suggestion, but I didn't find a good place for it, `find_home` suggest `FieldTheory.Adjoin`, but I didn't see places relavant with it, any suggestions about where to put it?
Yeah, maybe either adjoin or the relrank file (where you could probably also prove this using `IntermediateField.relrank_dvd_of_le_left`).

```suggestion
In this file, we prove the fundamental theorem of infinite Galois theory and the special case for
```

```suggestion
For any subgroup `H` of `Gal(K/k)` :
```
If typeclass inference already knows this, then is this line necessary? If it is, can you add a comment explaining why?
It could be deleted, it is only somehow needed while proving, nevermind.
Is this line necessary? Maybe write a comment saying why, if it is?
This can also be deleted, for the same unknown reason while proving.
`inferInstance` is the term, if you want to avoid going into tactic mode (probably saves a few milliseconds ;-) )
I doesn't know clearly why `inferInstance` failed here, it doesn't seem to work.

```suggestion
      simpa only [SetLike.coe_mem, true_implies]
```
From the `simpa` docs:
```
simpa [rules, â‹¯] will simplify the goal and the type of a hypothesis `this` if present in the context, then try to close the goal using the assumption tactic.
```
So it does exactly what your two lines do.

This is an equivalence right? What is the advantage of making it a Galois insertion? Surely the correct Galois insertion (or possibly coinsertion) is between intermediate fields and *all* subgroups (not just closed ones)? Because this gives you new information. It's an insertion (or coinsertion) because if you start with the field, then make the group, then make the field, it's the field you started with. The same isn't true for the groups of course, you end up with the closure of the group.

I'm slightly surprised that you can't just define the Galois insertion here in one line, invoking some result which says "an order isomorphism gives a Galois insertion". [looks in docs] yeah how about [OrderIso.toGaloisInsertion](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/GaloisConnection.html#OrderIso.toGaloisInsertion) ? I'm not clear what this is giving you.
I just copied these two results from the original `Galois` file, sorry that I doesn't know the reason clearly.
The one line proof works, I would take some time to figure out the one with subgroup instead of closed subgroup.
This is `OrderIso.toGaloisCoinsertion` I think?
